Text.Value: That's amazing, Jaheira. What can I do to help?
A pity. I could have used a young and powerful Jaheira.
In truth, I had put this ritual from my mind - until Last Light. Trapped in that darkness, I turned to my research again: what if I was a little stronger? As fast as I once had been?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Jaheira produces another rolled-up scroll and holds it up on 'I turned to my research again',. (no unfurling)

Text.Value: Of course I will, berserker. And you will sprout soft and golden locks from that shining skull.
And I am not blind. We have all profited from the results - perhaps the entire world will, before all of this is done.
So you plan to do it?

EditorData.logicalname: LOGIC NODE - Back to main questions after "Speak."

Text.Value: A noble sentiment. But I wonder if it would not lose some of its lustre, over the long years.
And if it does? That does not mean you cannot dig your heels in a little.
You're right. We have probably wasted enough words on this matter.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug, unmoved - she's as bad as we are, and plans to make up for it

Text.Value: So I will hold onto this a little longer, I think, and linger on - to see which one of us is right.
Enough of this cub stuff. My people live longer than yours, half-elf.
I do not speaking of clinging to life for its own sake. I just... look back on that life's work, and I wonder - is it done?
Well. That is entirely your problem now, cub.
Of course. It is our way - just as as it is death's way to meet us along the path, gently oblivious to whatever it is we want.
If the bards are right, then I've already done my share of deeds. But I can assure you, the work only ever feels half-finished at best.
Why stick around, if I'm so detestable?
Shrug.
Any druid. So yes, you might aspire to it if you wished. But the scroll is not the ritual itself - only part of my research into how it is worked.
You're not off the hook that easily, Jaheira. I want you around for a long time yet.
It is... a ritual. Or it describes one, at least. Practised by druids of certain esoteric circles.
Or proof that you plan to fight on, rather than take the easier path.
Knowing that - isn't it our duty to burn on if we can? To fight for as long as we are able?
Here I stand on only the humble three, half-cousin. But I hope I've filled them with my fair share of living.

EditorData.NodeContext: Humble three figures - SH references full elves' much longer lifespan, Jaheira is only a half-elf.

Text.Value: A little too philosophical for me.
You have cleared every obstacle in your path. Done everything that could be asked of you, without fear or favour. And without any regard for the cost.

EditorData.NodeContext: Alt scroll branch - she now WILL keep it, because we've proven to be violent and a little psychopathic at times. No venom or accusation in this - she's partof it too.

Text.Value: It's only natural to want more life.
Get over yourself, Harper. No one person can fix the world.
Death is a piss-poor excuse not to live. Who do you think I learned that from?

EditorData.NodeContext: Wry, fond - she's not denying that Karlach is dying or offering false comfort, but expressing respect for how Karlach deals with it.

Text.Value: Only, now - when I look at this, and think of all we have done, I realise: I was not worried. Not even afraid. I was arrogant.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mulling it over, telling us how she's changed her mind. She's chosen not to extend her life, because she's shown us someone will always come along to help - she's not needed, and a little amused at her own self-importance.

Text.Value: You see? I should know better than to philosophize in the company of an archdruid.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry, self-deprecating, Halsin put it better than she could have.

Text.Value: Something kept me from throwing it away. A fear, perhaps, that you were not the saviour you seemed to be.

EditorData.NodeContext: Alt scroll branch - she now WILL keep it, because we've proven to be violent and a little psychopathic at times. No venom or accusation in this - she's partof it too.

Text.Value: You will save us, of that I have no doubt, and I hope to be right by your side. But I have to believe the way we do it matters, too.
I believe that still. But, when I look on all we have achieved since, I wonder... perhaps it is not heroes we need. Only people who are willing to try.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mulling it over, telling us how she's changed her mind. She's chosen not to extend her life, because she's shown us someone will always come along to help - she's not needed, and a little amused at her own self-importance.

Text.Value: I do not know what manner of story that makes. But I do know that, without an ending, it would be no story at all.

EditorData.NodeContext: acknowledging this is maybe not as sexy as spinning a big tale of good and evil

Text.Value: I share my blame for pushing you down that path - for telling you that we must finish Ketheric at all costs.
I have no plans to lie down and die. Well - perhaps a little lying down, when all of this is done.
I worried that perhaps you were not the saviour you seemed. That Minsc was gone forever, and my family was doomed to see the city they love fall.
I spent most of my life fighting those who tried to escape their end. Ketheric, Irenicus, Sarevok... that is not company I would like to keep.
If you wish. It's possible I was a little too quick to judge. A little too caught up in ceremony.
And death might find us any moment. If I cannot meet it with a bit of cheerful futility, why bother being a Harper at all?
I'd consider it. I could achieve great things with another lifetime or ten...
I make no plans. Only... contingencies.
I'd cling to life forever if it means I could keep Baldur's Gate safe.

EditorData.logicalname: LOGIC - From "I found a secret scroll in your sanctuary..."

Text.Value: I cannot think what it is we have to talk about.

EditorData.NodeContext: Flat, giving us nothing. Last time we discussed this she stated her disapproval of us, and her mind hasn't changed.

Text.Value: Well-answered.
This city does not need me. It just needs someone. Baldur's Gate will never truly be saved, once and for all - but whatever it will be...

EditorData.logicalname: LOGIC - From "Can we talk about your scroll again"

Text.Value: And anyone can use this scroll...?
I'm honoured you think of me that way.
Everything I did was to save myself - save us all.
I hope that you will.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug, unmoved - she's as bad as we are, and plans to make up for it

Text.Value: If they be learned, and powerful enough, the practitioner of this ritual might slow their ageing. Extend their life well beyond its natural reach.
Perhaps you were not the saviour you seemed. I had learned better than to think of life as some simple tale, after all. There is no guarantee of happy endings, or true heroes.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining why she was hedging her bets - she'd grown cynical

Text.Value: In greener days, I might have been strong enough to do it. I might be yet, with the right preparations.
I'd take every drop of life I could get - especially for the sake of Baldur's Gate.
I accept - for as long as I'm able, at least.
Would you live on at any cost?
Do not look at me like that. I have been content to see the span of my natural years - a privilege far too few in this world can claim.
Or pleasing their own Undying Queen - who lives on to serve... what purpose, exactly?

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug, rhetorical

Text.Value: Hah! Do not thank me for slinging a weight around your neck. I might start to feel bad.
You know what I am, and you let me live.
I'd have thought time would dull either, but I suppose I should know better than to argue with an immortal.
To accept death is to surrender.
Did you think it would escape my notice forever? What you did to Isobel, in exchange for a little of your father's power?

EditorData.NodeContext: Alt scroll branch - she now WILL keep it, because we've proven to be violent and a little psychopathic at times. No venom or accusation in this - she's partof it too.

Text.Value: It is not something you need concern yourself with. I've picked up stranger things in all my travels, trust me.
And to fight it is to doom yourself to defeat.
Any druid. But the scroll is not the ritual itself. Only part of my research on its working.

EditorData.stateContext: JAHEIRA NOT HOLDING SCROLL ANY MORE

Text.Value: Don't get ahead of yourself. First we have to survive the Absolute.
Live forever? I'd be curious to hit four figures,  but it might get a little dull after that.
You have no right to judge me, Jaheira.
My feelings exactly.
And use it to do more than fight, I'd hope. Shar and Selûne have already claimed more than their share of your years, I think.
Perhaps. But if the darkness is really going to swallow everything, as you Sharrans say, it should at least have to work for its supper.
Did you think it would escape my notice forever? That you would trade Isobel away, to bring us closer to our goal?

EditorData.NodeContext: Alt scroll branch - she now WILL keep it, because we've proven to be violent and a little psychopathic at times. No venom or accusation in this - she's partof it too.

Text.Value: Do not be so sure. I was not always so soft and agreeable as I have become.
You're preaching to the doomed choir, ma'am.
Then you came, and made the question moot. But I kept this - just in case, I told myself. A final resort.
You have more in common with my people than you'd think. On the Astral Plane, our finest knights can live for millennia - and they devote every thought to vanquishing ghaik.
I do mean what I say - but I am also a Harper. In every honeyed word, there is a hook.
I'd cling to life forever if it means I could keep Baldur's Gate safe. But time marches me to a different fate.
So I will accept mine, when and however it comes. As for the this city's story, well...

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrugging

Text.Value: And age better too. She who is most weathered is also most wise.
Now come - our work isn't done yet.
But I have to believe that there is a better way.  So I will hold on to this for a little while, I think - and see which one of us is right.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Jaheira puts the scroll away (magic bum bag)

Text.Value: It is every Harper's hope to be a light that drives out darkness. But I've lived long enough to see so many of those lights burn out, while the shadows cling stubbornly on.
The threat of spanking never kept the children from poking through my things. Why should it deter you?
I wallowed in darkness for too long. If I could extend the time I have left in the light, I think I'd take it.
The darkness will prevail in the end, Jaheira. You're clinging on just to wage an unwinnable war.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'I wallowed...' = SH has turned from Shar. 'The darkness will prevail' = SH is loyal to Shar

Text.Value: You've done more than your share of fighting already, Karlach. If there is one person I would trust to make the most of a longer life, it is you.
I do not doubt you would serve her forever - only that she would let you. Strangely enough, those who grasp eternal life rarely mean for others to share in it.
Your duty, perhaps. Mine was quite the opposite. Every breath I take - however gratefully -  is proof of my dereliction.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mournful - referring back to Mystra's request he blow himself up

Text.Value: Perhaps not. But know that I judge myself every bit as harshly, for allowing this to come to pass.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug, unmoved - she's as bad as we are, and plans to make up for it

Text.Value: I know you would. But once the city squeezed it from you, what would be left? Everyone who seizes at eternal life has some purpose, in the beginning.
Because you will save us all. And I still hope you might do it the right way.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug, unmoved - she's as bad as we are, and plans to make up for it

Text.Value: Immortality is only as good as the life you're living. An eternity of luxury sounds a lot better than an eternity of struggle.
I would be eternal if it meant keeping my people free from ghaik slavery.
But I do not plan on going anywhere just yet. And besides - you still have a tadpole in your skull. You are almost certainly going to die first.
Minsc does not understand the question. You will live forever, Jaheira.
To wish to live is natural, but so too is to let go, when the moment arrives.
The Dead Three plague the world still. The city still falls prey to small minds like Gortash, or lost souls like Orin.
I would be eternal if it meant destroying ghaik for my queen.
Oh, you really think I'm pretty? Just a moment, while I remember how to bat my eyelashes.
And still will. Perhaps I could not stop you now, even if I wished it. But I hope I will not need to find out.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrug, unmoved - she's as bad as we are, and plans to make up for it

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: BRONZE VERSION: Jaheira puts the scroll away again (construct anim.)

Text.Value: Ah, I understand. I'd want to stay young and pretty too.

Synopsis: Jaheira's default dialogue. Topics range from her past life to her current goals as they develop. Unless otherwise stated, her tone is confident and to the point. She's a seasoned adventurer with a sardonic sense of humour - and a little less cynical than she might present herself to be.
